I made an engraving for a friend with a laser cutter. It's a Bloch sphere on thick blue acrylic and basically involved googling an image then pressing a couple buttons. 

A Bloch sphere represents all possible qubit states, where the distance from the top and bottom correspond to how much its in a 1 or 0 state.

I too did not meet the monthly harvest and have to submit late. This is a sketch of a tattoo I want to get eventually - it's kind of packing at least 3 ways of expressing recursion / self-reference.

So the headband has what's called the Y combinator on it, which broadly is an example of a fixed-point combinator. The wiki page for anonymous recursion is helpful if interested. Long story short is that you can think of recursive processes as repeated applications of a function on a fixed point (point that maps to itself: f(x)=x). squint at a normally written recursive process like f(n) =f(f(n-1))=... then just write the input as x and trust for now that the mathematical system (Lambda calculus) will take care of it right). So it's distilling the recursive structure out of functions which share that property.

The second is on the tummy and will be Andrea's rose (2nd pic for reference) which is a sick fractally origami flower. Third, it's a Russian nested doll.

content.text: Here is my (late) submission for March. I got a little caught up in the worldbuilding aspect of DnD and created a map of a theoretical region. I used my knowledge of geology and ecology to make a somewhat realistic map. I took into consideration prevailing winds, plate tectonics, and the rain shadow effects when mapping out the land features and biomes. I'm not sure if the placement of the towns/cities are realistic but this is definitely not its final form.

Gonna pop in for an early May submission. As you all know I am really into songwriting & recording guitar and vocals, however amateurish my muzikskillz might be. This group has helped me realize that one of the most fulfilling parts of the creation process is the sharing, even before I deem a thing completely done & perfect forever (cause more often than not, that never happens … & life is short). The things I’m currently calling my “songs” are — due to my nubile songwriting/recording and complete lack of production skills — not yet at a point where I feel they “qualify” for spotify or even bandcamp. but, I rlly do wanna share the skellingtons of songs that I create at this stage as a means of a) connecting with people I care about, like you peeps and other friends & family and b) sharing with other musically-inclined folks as a demo/bridge (to trick people into collaborating with me despite the fact that <https://open-book.ca/var/site/storage/images/news/i-have-no-idea-what-i-m-doing/1246-1-eng-CA/I-Have-No-Idea-What-I-m-Doing.jpg|I have no idea what I’m doing>).

If you’ve made it this far, wow, you’re a real homedog. <3 I present ye with my creation: *a Google Drive folder.* Inside that folder, you will find a handful of songs I’ve recorded over the past few months (a couple of which I’ve shared here before and a couple I haven’t). My current plan is to keep these files updated with the newest working versions of each of these things, plus to add more songs as I create them & deem them presentable-enough. Then I can just share the link with anyone who cares to listen to me, and they can theoretically bookmark it or something. (Which leads me to an open question for the group: is Google Drive even the best way to do this?)

Hopefully someday I can start doing live shows again with all this biz.

PS

As an added bonus, here's a sound file of a song I made sampling some guitar arpeggiation Isaac made a couple months back and then reworked into another long ass IDM banger.  I'll also add the original track Isaac sent me as a comparison to what I mean by processing.  I usually like to have multiple iterations of the same sample running at the same time at various speeds (2X//.5X)  and with different pitches (4ths/5ths/Octaves) to add complexity of sound and then have different effects chains to create a huge sound out of a single one.  If anyone who's making music likes this or wants any tips HMU and I'd love to give whatever limited insight I can.  I've also been taking piano lessons and started learning about musical theory again to up the ante, so hopefully the progress I've felt I've made continues and allows me to keep adding layers of abstraction and complexity that I so crave in music and it'll also allow me to help yall if you want it.

And here's my post for October, it started out with me and my roommates all recording takes of us saying all the phonemes of the English language, the basic building blocks of our language and progressed to me using a computer script to parse them together randomly with MIDI data, until they begin to trick the brain into hearing words seemingly out of nowhere.  The track starts super slow, around 20 BPM causing the vocal samples to remain the same pitch but be stretched to fill the gaps, which causes ableton to create digital artifacts from the process.  The track then speeds up until the words become rapidly fired around your headphones and speaker system like an avalanche.  I used my organs and synths to then provide a melodic and ambient background as the track slowly speeds up until they are filled in with a distorted and glitchy drum beat I made with my sequencers and fuddled around with.  Speeding up again to 150 BPM, the track peaks as a drum fill sample from the 60's comes in full blast and the song takes off into the sonic stratosphere.  The whole track is parallel routed through a Saturation pedal I have and begins peaking, but is brought back down to acceptable levels by a limiter function in Ableton which allows it to sit just on the cusp of being unusable for being too loud.  The track begins to slow once again to its original BPM with the drums following suit causing a new wave of artefacts to appear, with waves of noise made by my Korg MS-20 and the People's Guitar (A Circuit Bent WWE Toy Guitar) swimming around your head, leaving only ambient noise and the phonemes of my mates to close the track, starting how it began.  I also made a video accompaniment to go along with it, using VHS Footage I took at a music fest I attended recently.   Although I didn't spend too much time and effort on the video itself, it's amazing how the brain syncs the two together into a cohesive art piece and seemingly the visuals fit the audio and vice versa.  Hope you enjoy and what I wrote makes sense lol.

Here's my submission for this next month. Just a couple IDM bangers I whipped up over the weekend.  I'm still working on the overall structure, and I'm trying to get a couple friends to put on some trax for TTS, but overall they're coming along nicely. 

The first one TTS is an experiment in sampling.  I began by sampling my new roommate Matt playing bass harmonics and then used programming to trigger the different notes with MIDI and used probability and an RNG to make a generative melody. The rest of the song has a couple synth pads I made from scratch as the chord structure and a few old vinyls I sampled for the beats. The rest of the bleeps and bloops are from an old news segment on Text to Speech voice synthesis and an old TI speak and spell toy that I chopped up and put in the mix.  I was kind of going for a more jungle/kind of trip hop vibe and was inspired by the likes of flying lotus.

The second track is composed by heavily sampling the various FM (frequency modulation) synthesizers I have lying around. When pushed the right way, FM synth goes from cute and cheesy bell tones to extremely harsh and strange tones that I prefer.  The song also features the new house cat meowing that I play with MIDI to make strange squeaking sounds at the higher octaves and almost human like screams at the lower ones. Inspiration for this track is mainly aphex twin who often forgoes melody for harsh noise and strange samples over fast breakbeat.

A compilation me and the mates made recorded onto a tascam 4 track recorder that I'm borrowing from a friend.  It's been fun learning how to use this guy cuz it allows you to mix it all entirely on the machine by dividing the inputs from all the instruments on the 4 bands on each side of a cassette tape.  Routing is also an interesting limitation, since there's only 4 inputs, one for each band on the tape.  So I've been devising different methods of getting as many inputs as possible and I think these are the greatest results yet.  Currently, 6 drum mics are routed into a mixer and mixed down to a single L/R track with a good stereo image of the kit. Then the Guitar Amp, and Bass are mic'd and constitute input 2/3.  Lastly, all of our synths and a mic are routed into another mixer and bussed as a L/R input which allows for me to play maracas tambourine and synthesizer at the same time.  Later a second guitar was routed thru this very mixer, with FX sends added to everything, allowing for distortion, reverb and echo to be added to the signal while maintaining the initial tones of the instruments.

Obviously during the heat of a jam, mistakes are often made, the aforementioned guitar was put thru the distortion, but I pressed the wrong button on the mixer and it was routed into the mixer, but not the speakers we were listening on, so in the third track, the guitar sounds very hot and mangled, which was unintentional, but sounds pretty dern nice.

 The last track is created from a mistake I made flipping the cassette over during the jam, thinking it had run out of space.  Instead, the audio was reversed since the machine begins recording on the last 4 bands of tape without the need to flip it to increase the duration of recording.  I tried reversing it back to normal, but it honestly wasn't that great and sounded better in reverse, so I kept it.  Sonically we've been experimenting with more shoegaze music and it's definitely fun playing insanely loud.  Hope you enjoy

This month, I've been a busy bee and started learning about some fun new tech for visual art and processing.  First I wanted a method to make old VHS tapes I've shot look better on larger screens and modern TVs, so I began researching AI upscaling tech to try to make it work. 

 I demo'd a lot of different ones, some of them upscaled the resolution, but created unpleasant interlacing or warped the video to the point where it was useless. These were usually the ones that processed the video rather quickly.  Other ones that I gave up on required too much processing power and even requiring weeks to months of constant processing for rendering a 30 minute video on my roommate's modern gaming PC.  

Finally I settled on one that could process the normal cam footage I had as well as the visual art with feedback I've been doing that limited the rendering process to one of days instead of weeks.  Ultimately it is still an emergent technology, so it is not without limitations and drawbacks as well as creating artefacts, but  is also created by how you digitize the tapes in the first place, the age of the tape, as well as the lighting and other characteristics of the space it was shot in.  But now that I am aware of what works and what doesn't in this process I can start shooting footage with this type of post processing in mind to improve the quality of the upscaling, as well as continuing to find different programs that might work better or even look into ways of rendering on better computers with more VRAM.

But yeah, here's a selection of all the videos I "modernized" the first playlist is composed of footage from Spain, Bellingham parties, sunsets, and my recent trip to mount Baker.  I got a really good time lapse I'm proud of that I upscaled and sped up then made an hour loop with some ambient music I made to go over the top
 The end result is one that looks super professional, and really proud of the results.

Here's the visual art I've been making with an analog video mixer I recently picked up, where I am able to mix up to 4 video signals and do old school wipes/dissolves between them.  Because it has multiple outputs I can route one of them back into itself which creates video feedback, a vibrant, pulsating mutation of whatever is on the screen perfect for live shows or recording to tape for additional processing. These are a collection of different experiments I did, some where you chroma key (green screen) a specific colour, like the wall and then superimposing the feedback recording on top of a plain video, like our cat sleeping.  A still shot or time lapse can then become dynamic and constantly changing and trippy.  The output of the mixer that isn't being routed into itself is routed into my VHS player, so whatever I am making can be recorded instantly.  Then one of my other VHS players (I have 4 lol) can play this recording back into the mixer where I can layer or fade between a cam source and the visual tape for interesting results.  The applications for this are nearly limitless and I want to build a rack processing unit with this mixer and maybe a couple others hooked up to a projector so I can do live shows and start making money with the art.  I've also considered making these tape to sell or give to other tape fiends like myself, but we'll see where all this goes.  If anyone has an old VHS player lying around and would want a copy, hit me up.

Hey, sorry it's been a while. I got a new job with long hours and haven't been doing too much.  Here's my most recent obsession, little cathode ray tubes. I began amassing them a couple months ago and my collection is growing and the eventual goal is to create video art installations with them.  There's so many applications for the tech and they're dirt cheap if you know where to look.  All 8 of these guys cost probably around $60 bucks in total, since they're so unwieldy for the larger models.  

Currently I have 4 VHS players, my Waaave Pool (video glitch box), a Chromecast, a video mixer, video editor for cranking dat sweet sweet saturation and a few cams, including a security cam that uses VHF to wirelessly transmit into one TV.   All of these sources can be endlessly blended into one another, recorded, and generally mixed up to create art ranging from subtle psych to full blown seizures of which I can record and digitize at a later date.  

My next big projects include an art installation where a video of my eye  bugging out is transmitted to two small TV's atop a larger one with footage of my mouth sneering, smiling and making other uncomfortable faces, creating an unnerving staring recreation of my face.

Another project I've got in the works is a rework of video wall projects for stores that combine multiple screens as a single feed.  To do this I will be using a raspberry pi to split an analogue signal into a grid and assign separate outputs for each of the TV's.  This might be difficult, since I'm still not that adept at coding, but there's a lot of sources from smarter people that I've been bookmarking.  If my description isn't enough, try looking up TV wall art installations.

Another little video idea I've been toying with is integrating my music gear to interface with the old tech.  I've seen some really neat videos of people who use Control Voltage or MIDI from instruments routed into a computer to control a video feed on a computer.  So basically, you would play a note on a keyboard and the computer reads this information and can apply trippy effects in real time or can shuffle along to different parts of a video based off the note you play.

I've also been seeing some people who are using two TV's a tube and slanted mirrors to make it seem as though a video is hopping between the two TV's like they were alive. It also can create an almost holograph effect where it looks like an image is suspended in the air.  

Anyways, these are all the ideas I've got so far running in my head, perhaps a bit ambitious, but I've already come leaps and bounds in the last couple months, so I'm confident.  It'd be great to eventually combine this with music for shows if I ever get that far.
